body:
Verilator version: Verilator 5.027 devel rev v5.026-110-g18fc3e608
OS: Ubuntu 22.04 LTS
We are open to solving the issue ourself with some help.

When the RTL has an instance of a packed struct whose elements are assigned in multiple places, for example in multiple procedural blocks or procedural blocks and output ports of a module, the assignment of a structure member can be skipped or incorrect. 

In the attached regression test, a module outputs both one-hot and binary versions of a value. Internal to the module, a packed struct was added to hold the values that drive the two output ports. One of the structure elements is assigned by an `assign` statement, and the other is assigned via an `always_comb` block. It appears that the conditional assignment in the always_comb block is skipped.

For this test, the problem will not occur if we add `/*verilator split_var*/` to the structure variable declaration. However, in the original case in which we discovered this, when we add that pragma, we get the following error:

```'structure_variable_name' has split_var metacomment but will not be split because its bit range cannot be determined statically```

It’s not clear what it is about the specific struct that causes Verilator to emit this error, and we were unable to recreate this behavior in our regression test.

[t_split_var_comb.zip](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/16552297/t_split_var_comb.zip)

```

module Test
(
    input wire clk,
    input wire rst,

    output logic [1:0] one_hot,
    output logic binary
);
   always_ff @(posedge clk) begin
      one_hot[1] <= one_hot[0];
      one_hot[0] <= one_hot[1];

      if (rst) begin
         one_hot <= 2'b01;
      end
   end

   struct packed {
      logic [1:0] one_hot;
      logic binary;
   } nets_in_struct;
  
   assign nets_in_struct.one_hot = one_hot;

   always_comb begin      
      nets_in_struct.binary = '0;

      if (nets_in_struct.one_hot[1]) begin
         nets_in_struct.binary = 1'b1;
      end

      binary = nets_in_struct.binary;        
   end
endmodule
```
